column1: This digest can boast of three new versions of AdGuard products. Besides, we filled the blog to the brim with interesting articles! Learn more about how X spreads unmarked ads and mobile carriers make money off your data.
AdGuard v7.15 for Windows: Now with HTTP/3 filtering

We are pleased to introduce AdGuard v7.15 for Windows, equipped with HTTP/3 filtering. This feature, powered by our latest CoreLibs v1.12, uses the QUIC network protocol instead of the TCP transport layer protocol, providing increased privacy and security. Aside from HTTP/3 filtering, we’ve addressed a few bugs and made several improvements to boost the overall performance of AdGuard for Windows.
AdGuard v4.2 for Android: Dynamic theme and HTTP/3 filtering support

In this release, AdGuard introduces dynamic themes and icons! With the dynamic theme selected (available to users with Android 12+) AdGuard will match its color scheme to your system's colors. We've also rolled out experimental HTTP/3 filtering and support for dual HTTPS certificates. Indeed, these updates cater to both casual and tech-savvy users alike!
AdGuard v1.11.15 for Safari: Now on macOS Sonoma!
We’re proud to introduce the latest version of AdGuard for Safari. Our main focus here was to ensure compatibility with the new macOS Sonoma, which included improving our extension overall.
Elon, what the ad?? Unmarked ads flood X
X is now experimenting with removing “ad” labels from regular ads, as well as introducing ads that cannot be reported at all. What's going on, and what to do? We explain.
How mobile carriers make money off your data behind your back

We pay mobile operators a monthly fee to use the Internet and make calls. But what many of us don’t realize is that mobile operators are not just providing a service, but also collecting and selling our personal data.
Cloudflare says Encrypted Client Hello might ‘solve privacy for good’. The reality is not that simple

Encrypted Client Hello (ECH) is being touted as the technology that can finally solve the privacy problem. Mozilla and Cloudflare are betting big on it. But unfortunately it is not foolproof, and should not be regarded as a panacea against surveillance. Why? Let’s find out together.
Meta’s rumored astronomical fee for Instagram and Facebook in EU: greedy much or just not serious?
Meta reportedly plans to charge nearly $20 for a combination of Facebook and Instagram on mobile devices without ads. They can't be serious, can they?

column1: The secret of Incognito mode: clear mask, not invisibility cloak

Almost every browser has a special mode that promises to hide your browsing history. Sometimes it is called ""private"" or, as in the case of Google Chrome, ""incognito mode"". The name suggests that what you do online will be shrouded in an extra veil of secrecy.

But it's not quite that simple. Dressed in your fedora hat and round glasses — Chrome's signature incognito mode symbols — you're as visible as ever to trackers, websites, your school, your employer, and your ISP. Your disguise is not blown; it never was!

Arguably the only thing this mode does for you is protect your browsing history from other users of the same device. All the while, the boogeymen are keeping a close eye on you. Find out how to protect yourself from spooks and the like for real.
Google becomes the Grim Reaper of the open web

A new API proposed by Google threatens to turn the Internet into a walled garden, accessible only to users of certain devices and browser settings. Ad-blocking users could find themselves being locked out.
AI drone goes full Frankenstein on its handlers

An AI-powered army drone defied its orders and turned fire on its human operator after being stopped from killing the target. This is a thought experiment, so no one actually died. But it is a sinister omen for the future.
A potent three-letter spell that breaks ChatGPT

ChatGPT is an AI-powered genie that you can assign all sorts of tasks to — write code, analyze text, create a film script. But it won't do just anything — violent things are a no-go. However, there is one way…
Encrypted Client Hello: not a magic potion, but will help your privacy

Encrypted Client Hello is a new protocol that encrypts the last remaining unencrypted part of your connection with a website. Some say ECH will even ‘solve’ privacy for good. But we don’t believe in fairy tales.
The Iron Man's fall: Musk unleashes unlabelled ads on X users
Once the inspiration behind a controversial Marvel hero, Elon Musk is now littering X (formerly Twitter) with unlabelled spammy ads. The reason: likely, money. Find out what can be done about it.

column1: You are paying twice for your mobile Internet

How much does your cell phone plan cost? Probably too much. But unfortunately, your monthly fee is not the only way you pay your carrier: you also trade your data — web history, call history, app usage — for the privilege of surfing the Web and making calls.

More often than not, this part of the trade happens unbeknownst to you. Wireless carriers like Verizon, T-Mobile, and AT&T automatically enroll you in one of their data-sharing (or should we say data-selling?) programs. These programs allow them to collect and share your personal information with third parties for targeted ads and marketing.

Even more sinister and privacy-unfriendly are the opt-in advertising programs that you may find yourself signing up for inadvertently, or because they’ve convinced you that your quality of service will suffer if you don’t. So, how can you break free from the surveillance chains and unwanted data trade?
The Big Brother is tracking you
A hidden system that ranks you based on your calls

How often, who, and when you call — everything can be tracked and factored in towards your ‘reputation score.’ This score, calculated without your knowledge, can then be used to deny you access to certain services.
Is your country best or worst in terms of tracking?

Almost every website you visit is swarming with ad trackers, placed there by marketers to follow you around the web. But it turns out that the number of trackers varies from country to country. Find out where yours stands.
How social media spy on you… and on your cat

Don’t believe a social media platform when it says it’s private and your confidential information is safe with it. That’s a lie. Its employees can easily tap into this data thanks to ‘internal tools’ and spy on you.
This AI chatbot has a big problem
AI-powered chatbots are not only useful, but also dangerous. This one, integrated with a popular search engine, may serve you malware disguised as ads.
Instagram and FB without ads — but there’s a catch
No ads on Instagram and Facebook? Sounds like something out of a parallel reality. But that could soon be the case in the EU. The catch is you'll have to pay a fortune for your subscription.
How Snap uses AI to lure kids into sharing their data
A friendly-looking avatar powered by AI, integrated with a social media platform targeting kids. You almost can’t help but chat with it. But beware: the consequences can be dire for your privacy.

column1: We’ve survived Google’s new extension API: it’s not that bad

When Google Chrome announced Manifest V3, a new platform for building extensions, it sparked a lot of controversy and criticism. Many developers, including us, worried about reduced functionality. Some doomsayers even predicted that it would spell the end of ad blocking.

At first, we strongly opposed the proposed API. But as Chrome began listening to feedback and suggestions, and fixing flaws and making changes, we began to see some potential benefits in MV3. Don’t get us wrong: we still think the platform is far from ideal, and we don’t appreciate Google taking away some of our blocking capabilities that had benefited our users.

But it’s not the end of the world. Ad blockers have survived, and AdGuard led the way in adapting to the new platform <https://email-link.adtidy.org/email.html?m=257c7b7u4b&l=kYVUPBjUefQY5gdlKlbTCVCN5JU7gaizO6m3nVcGpBBUcRsswEEsgBtDJ5wvJn0SOhou98pNOgplAT8Be4d42vO2utgsJgeTQOZfN8jER8fE51uz0F40wTF5bkjqG0uEVUmu360AlLuQs7iGJkBB4B2kFSVEoCWlCDWRr2l35x31nj2jaLzylWOljJT7k7D0GUutFvwUZpVeVTeiJIxNuj4> . After all, MV3 has some pros, such as improved performance and cross-platform compatibility. For a deeper dive into the topic, check out the article by AdGuard CTO Andrey Meshkov.
People are worried about their online privacy, but won’t act
A study has found that more and more people are concerned about how their online data is used, but don’t think they can make a difference even with their best effort. How did we get there?
Windows Phone comes back from the dead to block ads
Halloween may be over, but zombies are still lurking in the shadows. The long-dead Windows Phone OS is back to block YouTube ads by spoofing the user agent. But we don't recommend this method.
Why the dominance of Google and Apple stores is bad

For many casual Internet users, there are only two app stores: Google Play and the App Store. The duo rules the market in an arbitrary manner, costing both developers and users not only additional expenses, but also innovation.
A powerful publisher wanted ad blockers banned, but failed

A German publisher wanted the court to find that ad blockers violated copyright law by modifying the code of the website. If the court had sided with the publisher, it would've meant damages not only for developers, but also for users.
Why we shunned Google Play. Or did it shun us?

Why can’t you find AdGuard for Android on Google Play Store? It’s not because we’re too proud to be there. It’s because Google, who makes money from ads, doesn’t like some apps. We reveal the whole story.

column2: New US bill aims to finally limit warrantless surveillance, including the collection of information from smart cars <https://email-link.adtidy.org/email.html?m=257c7b7u4b&> . Fingers crossed

Bilgisayar Game Pass aboneliğinizin süresi yakında sona erecek

Bilgisayar Game Pass aboneliğinizin süresi 16 Aralık 2023 Cumartesi tarihinde dolacak. Bu tarihten sonra, pazara çıktıkları gün yeni oyunlar ve EA Play kataloğu da dahil olmak üzere 100'den fazla kaliteli bilgisayar oyununa erişiminizi kaybedeceksiniz.
Forza, Halo ve Minecraft gibi en sevilenlerden It Takes Two gibi ödüllü başyapıtlara kadar her şeyi oynamaya geri dönmek için aboneliğinizi bugün gözden geçirin.
Tarihler her Eşgüdümlü Evrensel Saat için görüntülenir. Sipariş tarihi konumunuza göre değişebilir.

column1: This AI chatbot says it’s private — we put it through its paces

OpenAI's ChatGPT, Microsoft's Bing AI, and Google's Bard – they are all at the forefront of the new generation of AI-powered chatbots that are smarter and more effective. But none of them can boast a stellar privacy record, either in their own right or by association. However, a new chatbot by privacy-focused browser Brave, claims to change all that.

The new chatbot, Leo, says it won't store your chats or use them to train AI — it’ll only be there to help you. And its promise of ""unparalleled privacy” is too tempting not to test. So we did. And the results were a mixed bag, both in terms of helpfulness and privacy.

Leo would assure us that it does not know where we are, while correctly guessing our time. And when we confronted it on this, its answers slipped further into ambiguity. If you're as curious as we were about the new chatbot and its ""real"" location — yes, it did spill some beans to us — check out the article.
How AI-supercharged search fares against traditional Google?
Microsoft has integrated an AI-powered chatbot into its Bing search engine. The chatbot is free, chatty, often helpful but also not unbiased. We’ve tried it to see how it stacks up against Google.
AI tries its hand it blocking ads, but it’s kinda shaky

A GPT-Adblocker promises to detect and remove all ads from YouTube videos, even those that are embedded in the content itself. We’ve put it through a series of rigorous tests, and we’re not that impressed.
Google is putting AI in search: ads everywhere
Not to be outdone by its competitors, Google is building an AI assistant into its revamped search experience. For good or bad? It's hard to say, but ads seem to take center stage.
Ads expose you to government surveillance

In the online ads industry, real-time bidding (RTB) is when your data is auctioned off to the highest bidder among advertisers. But because these auctions are open to almost anyone, anyone can get a piece of your life for peanuts, even the government.
How to deal with spam — a comprehensive guide

Online spam, or junk mail, has been around as long as the Internet. It's a scourge we all hate, but despite our best wishes and efforts, it refuses to go away. We've put together a list of services and tools that can help.

column1: 7 browsers that offer a more private alternative to Chrome

Google Chrome might be dominating the market, but it’s plagued by privacy woes. There are plenty of more privacy-friendly alternatives that put Chrome to shame and are equally or nearly as fast and feature-rich.

In our guide, we've picked out the most popular of these browsers for which privacy isn't just a buzzword. They are Firefox, DuckDuckGo, Brave, Opera, Safari, Vivaldi, and, of course, Tor, without which no list of ""most private"" would be complete. We looked under their hoods and cranked up their privacy settings to the max.

Choosing a private search engine, protecting your emails, blocking all cookies, banishing ads with in-built filters, or even enabling a VPN — they are all on the menu. You are one step away from going private — check out our guide.
Extensions can steal your data: how to minimize risk

Extensions give your browser more capabilities, but they also can steal your passwords and other personal information. This does not mean, however, you should stop using them. Find out how to choose them wisely.
Online privacy is important, but tricky. Find out whether you check all the 19 boxes in our all-comprehensive digital hygiene checklist.
How to send an anonymous email: an exhaustive guide
An anonymous email account is a must-have if you want to keep your inbox clean and safe. The disposable mail will take care of the spam, and make your online identity less traceable across the web.
Everything you need to know about cookies

Cookies are not just delicious treats, they are also tiny text files that websites can secretly store in your browser. Find out what are the differences between first-party and third-party cookies, and what are the pros and cons of blocking them.
A search engine from ChatGPT-maker: Will it kill Google Search?
OpenAI, the company behind ChatGPT, is developing a search service that aims to rival Google Search. Leveraging its AI skills and fame, will it be a formidable contender?

column1: The leap year brought an extra day to February, and we, of course, took advantage of every single minute of this atypical month to bring you 2 releases for our browser extensions and a complete coverage of the latest privacy news. Discover Apple’s strategy to maintain its App Store monopoly in the EU, dive into the risks behind push notifications on iOS, and take a look at our take on OpenAI’s upcoming search engine.
Apple is opening its walled garden to rival app stores and payment providers in the EU. The catch is — the new rules are accompanied by a prohibitive fee.
AdGuard Browser Extension MV3 v0.4.0: time to update

It’s been almost a year and a half since we released the MV3-based extension, and it’s time for a major update. Please welcome: an improved version of the first ad blocking extension that works on Manifest V3.
AdGuard Browser Extension v4.3: differential filters update
We bring you the new version of AdGuard Browser Extension with significant changes! We added the differential filters update capability, so now your ad-blocking experience will get even better.
TikTok, Meta, and others exploit push notifications to collect data

You never know where the next hit to privacy will come from. A number of popular apps have been taking advantage of a push notification feature on iOS to harvest data about users’ applications and hardware.
ChatGPT-based search engine: a Google Search challenger?
ChatGPT maker OpenAI is said to be preparing to take on Google with a new search product. A worthy challenger for Google Search, finally?
Why do people use VPNs and how?
We’ve asked you and here are the answers. Find out why people from different parts of the world use a VPN service and what they value the most in terms of features.

column1: VPNs’ popularity is on the rise: what is the appeal?

As we spend more and more time online, we leave more and more footprints on the Web that we may not want to leave behind. VPNs (Virtual Private Networks) are probably one of the best and easiest tools to protect our privacy and anonymity online, and they have become increasingly popular over the years.

But using a VPN, a service that connects a user's device to the Internet through a secure tunnel, is not just about protecting your privacy. Want to stream shows from halfway across the globe or snag deals that are usually out of reach? VPN’s got your back.

We asked you, our readers from around the world, what you value most in a VPN, why you use it, and what's the deal breaker for you. The results vary depending on how often you hit the connect button and where you're located. The big takeaway? We're all showing a growing awareness of online privacy and our need to keep the Internet open and free.
Popular iOS apps track you through notifications

A number of popular apps, X, TikTok, and Facebook Messenger among them, take advantage of a push notification feature on iOS to collect device data and send that information off to a third party, such as your insurance provider.
This is how targeted ads rat you out to cops

For the online advertising industry, our personal data is its greatest resource: data brokers harvest it, bid on it, buy it, and sell it. What is hidden behind the scenes is that this data often lands in the hands of law enforcement.
Your phone plays fast and loose with your data

Research has shown that some Android phones come with pre-installed apps that quietly gather your GPS location, call logs, and even your phone number. iPhones are also in on the game, scooping up tons of data to send back to their makers.
Ad and tracking wall of shame: which countries have it the worst?

In our report on a share of ad trackers in the global Internet traffic, we estimate how much of your bandwidth is eaten up by ad server requests, compare these figures across different countries, and examine the trends over time.

column1: Apple mocks EU regulation with new developer terms

Apple faces a deadline of March 6 to comply with the new European antitrust law that aims to give developers more freedom over how and where they distribute their apps and how they charge users. The law, known as the Digital Markets Act (DMA), forces ‘gatekeepers’ like Apple’s App Store and its iOS operating system to open up to competition or face a potentially devastating fine.

But Apple is not opening up without a catch. Apple offers developers a choice: either stick to the old terms, or accept new terms and gain the right to use alternative stores and payment methods. However, if developers opt for the latter, they will have to pay a steep Core Technology Fee (CTF).

The CTF is charged for every new install after an app reaches 1 million annual users, and it may cost developers millions of dollars. The new fee could spell doom for free and freemium apps — that is, if they choose to accept the new terms. But chances are, no one will — which suits Apple’s agenda just fine.
AdGuard VPN: Your ally against Turkey’s VPN ban

Turkey is expanding its crackdown on VPN services. The latest attack targeted 16 VPN providers, but AdGuard VPN is still up and operating. We are giving all our Turkish users 10GB of free traffic and an 83% discount <https://email-link.adtidy.org/email.html?m=9ln45pao3h&l=6JDRmgL6pivHlf8PnsbLUOq2kbzNBgxSef1UXaSm4bLTQcjgOy22fWnxJ1S1jtG7jGTHpQz2kh43CaSyjQ8QBbVf3xylrPJUFrW2h2xJc7c8SlEy8yEyZ8C4fE7i3TxpowRa9qWtyoiwH55YdteSJYPeIr8f5RSeXwt5FcrmBIUtj9gtf2qL1E3AuT4eFfc1fBWZKxHhlelvw5h1fa7BVISuUCUileWBi1UmPzF9sAySX> .
Ring stops (some) police requests for videos

Ring, a security camera company owned by Amazon, has scrapped a feature in its app that let police ask Ring customers to share their videos. This may sound like a win for privacy advocates, but it does not mean Ring cannot see your private videos. Find out how.
The Google and Apple’s duopoly is a problem
Google and Apple run app market show to the ground

Apple's App Store and Google's Play Store impose their strict rules on developers and demand steep cuts. And if you argue with them, you're likely to lose. Telegram learned that lesson the hard way. But there's light at the end of the tunnel.
AdGuard ad blocker is not on Google Play. Why?

You won't find our flagship app, AdGuard Ad Blocker for Android, in the Google Play Store. This is the result of Google's purge of some, but not all, content blocking apps. Find out what happened and where we stand.

column1: This digest covers the release of our new product — AdGuard Temp Mail, the historical ban on a data broker in the US, and Google’s take on Chrome’s Incognito Mode. We also take a look at the face-off between YouTube and ad blockers, as well as the problems with Chrome’s 3rd party cookie replacement.
Keep your inbox clean with AdGuard Temp Mail
AdGuard Temp Mail is an email generator designed to protect your main inbox from spam, and you — from tracking. Try AdGuard Temp Mail for free and see if it comes in handy for you.
Did ad blockers survive YouTube’s offensive?
YouTube tried to block video playback for ad-blocking users last year. Some even thought that this global effort would lead to the demise of ad blockers. But that did not happen.
3rd party cookie replacement turns Chrome into an ad auction tool
Chrome has begun phasing out third-party cookies, the infamous tracking tool, for 1% of its users. Why is this happening? And how good is the replacement?
US govt bans location data broker from selling sensitive data
The US government has banned a location data broker from spilling users’ sensitive information to government contractors and others without consent. This is great news, but is it enough?
Google admits Chrome’s Incognito Mode is not so private
When you switch to Incognito mode in Chrome, Google is still able to see everything you’re doing there, the company itself admitted. At long last.
Ring’s new policy limits police access to user footage

Ring is disabling a feature in its app that allowed the police to talk to users via direct message, limiting the access to footage from their security cameras without a warrant. This is a step in the right direction.

column1: Google has long claimed that its Incognito mode lets you ""browse privately."" But this could not be further from the truth. Incognito mode does little more than hide your browsing history from other users of your device. In fact, Chrome's Incognito mode disclaimer has long admitted that your employer and the websites you visit can still track your activity.
But that was never the whole story. Google conveniently omitted that it was also collecting your data from the websites that use its analytics tools — which is more than half of the Internet.

Now, after a $5 billion lawsuit, Google is having to come clean about its role in spying on users in Incognito mode. This is a win for transparency, but it still does not mean much for privacy. Our advice: do not trust Incognito mode and its false but oh-so-tempting promise.
AdGuard Temp Mail is here to protect your mailbox

We've launched AdGuard Temp Mail — a free temporary email address generator. You get an anonymous, disposable email address to sign up for services you don't trust or that are spammy. Try it for yourself! <https://email-link.adtidy.org/email.html?m=8emt2j5szf&l=kYVUPBjUefQY5gdlKlbTCUobO6CzWfstKqdl2V0tX6WpRM0e7Z6x0i6tjAnjQ6jO9PaRga7s7tfK0xsH7VRt4bAeAcIAeFBwknKhuqv7NluGCI6GZeXLemj9nuhei3uGh1uPE4brQRcmxtqDa76ab9TH0PB4AzcImkMtFfoyqVUEFv34YOZw8B81KdBX2RlhhA5RbRjFTr25yrQ7moxdngO>
US punishes data broker for selling sensitive info

We've been waiting for this moment for a while: in a historic first, the FTC has banned a location data broker from using and selling location data without explicit user opt-in. A slap on the wrist for the industry, or a game changer?
AdGuard DNS finds a solution to a common privacy issue

EDNS Client Subnet is a mechanism widely used by DNS resolvers to deliver location-specific results to clients. However, it has its flaws: it deals a blow to your privacy and negatively affects caching. Read about how AdGuard DNS finds a solution to these problems.
Dissecting Incognito mode and its false promise

Incognito mode is neither anonymous nor private, but Google's deceptive marketing has led many to believe otherwise. We took a scalpel to Incognito mode and showed just how much tracking goes on behind the scenes.
Smart toys are cute, but how safe are they?

Children today crave interactive dolls, toy cameras and karaoke mics with Bluetooth, and parents are tempted to settle for nothing less. These flashy gadgets seem harmless, but they hide a serious threat to privacy and security.

column1: We are saying goodbye to shareable pages
From today, you will no longer be able to create new shareable pages, and from February 21, all existing shareable pages will be removed.

Don’t worry, though - you can continue to share your assets through our current social media integrations, or you can also create a shareable link when you connect your OneDrive account. Find out more here.
To keep accessing your existing shareable pages, you can download your previously shared videos and save them to your computer or OneDrive.
If you need help, our friendly support team are on hand.
Follow the Clipchamp community for more tips
This email was sent to relax_gamer3@hotmail.com by Clipchamp at Microsoft.

column1: Here’s our new product: AdGuard Temp Mail. Like all our products, it’s designed to protect your privacy. What’s unique?
Imagine: You’re about to sign up for a service but that email field… You just know your inbox will soon be flooded with spam.
Solution #1: Go ahead and hope that your email address will remain confidential.
Solution #2: Use a temporary email address.
We like the second one. That’s why we’ve developed our own secure email address generator. Check it out — it’s free and requires no registration.
Simple as that: Get a temporary email address, use it where you need it, and receive emails. Spam? Just generate a new email address. The previous one will be deleted along with its inbox.
AdGuard Temp Mail is currently in beta stage. There’s much more to come! We’ve described our plans for the future and left detailed instructions in our blog post.
Protect all your devices from ads
Makes you anonymous and your traffic inconspicuous
Helps control web traffic on all your devices
Got questions about AdGuard Ad Blocker? Contact our support team <mailto:support@adguard.com> .

column1: Ad blockers weathered the YouTube storm

Last year was marked by an intensified crackdown on ad blocking by YouTube. The Google-owned video-playing and ad-serving behemoth took on ad blockers in earnest, bombarding their users with ominous warnings and cutting off video playback for them.

As the tug-of-war heated up, some went so far as to predict the imminent demise of ad blockers. In reality, however, ad blockers not only learned to outmaneuver YouTube’s ever-changing anti-adblock scripts, but also managed to piggyback off the media attention surrounding the YouTube’s crusade.

The number of uninstalls spiked, but so did the number of installs. And when it comes to the number of active users, YouTube's offensive ended up not having much of an impact on our expectations. Check out the article below to see for yourself (cool graphs included!).
Take part in a VPN survey

Do you use a VPN? And if so, what are the main reasons you need it? We want to pick your brain to help us better protect your privacy and security. Don't worry, the survey is completely anonymous and won't reveal any of your personal info.

Chrome, the world's most popular browser, is finally getting rid of third-party cookies. These are used to track you around the web, making them a privacy threat. But the supposedly privacy-friendly replacement is not much better. Find out why.
iPhone’s new feature raises privacy concerns

Apple's new feature, NameDrop, makes it easy to share contacts between two iPhones. But US authorities are raising the alarm bells over it. Is it such a privacy threat, or are they making much ado about nothing?
This AI chatbot is very private, or so it claims

Brave is best known for its privacy-focused browser. But recently it also released a privacy-focused AI chatbot called Leo. AI and privacy, are they even possible in the same sentence? We investigate.
This technology promises to 'solve privacy for good'

A new technology deployed by Cloudflare holds a lot of promise — it aims to secure the very first part of the ‘hello’ message your device sends to the browser. But as cool as it seems, it’s too early to celebrate.

column1: The evolution of ad tracking: a country-by-country analysis

Ads never — or rarely — travel alone. They are almost always accompanied by trackers, responsible for following you online. We call such two-headed hydras “ad trackers”. Whenever you visit a website on any device, you are not only loading the desired content, but also the ad trackers that come with it.

Ad trackers distract you from reading, make the page load slower, and drain your device’s battery, all while sending your personal data and information about your interests to advertisers and other third parties. In our new report, we estimated that ad trackers can account for up to 20% of your traffic, and if it sounds like a lot, that’s because it is.
The numbers vary by country. So if you're curious about the proportion of ad tracker traffic in your country and how it's changed since last year, we suggest you take a look at our report.

The year 2023 has been an eventful one for AdGuard: we've completely redesigned our Android app, added Android TV support, migrated AdGuard's ad blocking and VPN extensions to MV3, and brought new and exciting features to the desktop apps. More to come!
Blocking ads on the big screen: AdGuard for Android TV

It has always been a struggle to protect yourself from ads and trackers on Android TV. That's why we decided to take matters into our own hands and give you an easy to use method that works! AdGuard for Android TV is specifically designed to block ads on your TV. Learn how to set it up.
Do people care about tracking at all?

In plain words, tracking means surveillance, either by corporations or the government, and both are bad. The new survey shows that people are increasingly concerned about what happens to their data online, but have little idea how to protect it.
Cookies — the linchpins of online tracking

Cookies, and we're not talking about those soft, chewy chocolate chip cookies that everyone loves, but ""tracking cookies,"" have long been the kings of the targeted ads industry. Find out what they are and how to block them.
Your car is likely tracking you, too

Your modern car is a spy on wheels. It watches your every move and listens to your every word with sensors and cameras. And it’s not alone. Your phone and your infotainment system are also snitches that feed your data to the maker.

column1: We are pleased to announce that AdGuard for Windows now comes in a 64-bit version. It is about time, as most Windows computers today are 64-bit, with more processing power and memory than their 32-bit predecessors. We believe this will result in a more efficient and responsive experience for our users.

column2: If you’re still using a 32-bit computer, don't worry! Our system will automatically detect it and provide you with the appropriate version.

column1: We are saying goodbye to shareable pages

On February 21, 2024, Clipchamp will be saying goodbye to our shareable pages feature. From January 21, you will no longer be able to create new shareable pages, and from February 21, all existing shareable pages will be removed.

Don’t worry, though - you can continue to share your assets through our current social media integrations, or you can also create a shareable link when you connect your OneDrive account. Find out more here.
To keep accessing your existing shareable pages, you can download your previously shared videos and save them to your computer or OneDrive.
If you need help, our friendly support team are on hand.
Follow the Clipchamp community for more tips
This email was sent to relax_gamer3@hotmail.com by Clipchamp at Microsoft.

column1: Smarter doesn’t always mean better — not with smart toys

We're in that unique time frame where there's still ample opportunity to find the perfect gift for your loved ones before the holiday rush, but time is running out. At least when it comes to choosing gifts for your kids, it's pretty clear — toys, right? And considering the modern age, a smart toy should be the obvious choice.

But like all other 'smart' devices such as TVs and fridges, smart toys pose significant privacy risks. Whenever microphones and cameras are involved, personal data is at risk, and in the case of smart toys, it's your children's privacy that's at stake.

Research by the US Public Interest Research Group reveals concerning findings about smart toys. Manufacturers either overlook privacy safeguards, leaving security vulnerabilities, or actively collect extensive personal data from children themselves. Check out the article for more details and tips for selecting the ideal gift for your child.
Is your home your private castle?
Among all the things you don't want to go rogue, baby monitors are near the top of the list. Yet, so many of them lack necessary security mechanisms and can be easily hacked.
Vacuum cleaners: dust or data collectors?

A robot vacuum is a staple of many a household. The more advanced models can even take photos of their surroundings. To better navigate around the house, of course… but also to leak your intimate pics on Facebook.

It's not only about vacuum cleaners, baby monitors, and smart TVs: so many gizmos we drag around with us all day. And they are not an ounce safer that their stationary counterparts. If anything, they are even more dangerous.
A new iPhone feature that simplifies sharing of contacts has been branded a threat to privacy by the US law enforcement. Is it really so dangerous? We investigate.

column1: As September waves goodbye, the time comes for that beloved cliché: adding ""Wake Me Up When September Ends"" to our playlists and diving headfirst into the nostalgia pool. But, hey, if you’ve actually been hitting the snooze button all month, no worries – we’ve got you covered with a roundup of the latest privacy news, from Malaysia’s DNS censorship to the new ads on YouTube, plus three exciting AdGuard releases.
Mozilla removes ad-tracking code from Firefox
Mozilla removes ad-tracking code from Firefox mobile browsers. Is this an attempt at damage control, a response to criticism, or a mere technicality?
AdGuard Browser Extension finally migrates to MV3
The journey of adapting to Google’s new API Manifest V3 is over and we present you with a new release: Our browser extension for Chrome is now fully functional.
Pause ads on YouTube: A new annoyance in your streaming routine
YouTube has started rolling out pause ads to users globally. What are they, and what can you do about them?
AdGuard VPN v2.4 for Mac: with an advanced feature and improved stability
With version 2.4, you can select subnets whose traffic should not be routed through AdGuard VPN and enjoy better performance thanks to the updated VPN protocol.
Brazil bans X and targets VPN users
Brazil has blocked X (formerly Twitter) over Elon Musk’s refusal to comply with the order to appoint a local representative. Brazilians are now facing fines for accessing X.
AdGuard VPN v2.4 for Windows: better UX and better compatibility
Version 2.4 comes in a 64-bit form and with handy UX improvements. They will help you better understand how Exclusions work and assist with potential problems you may encounter while using the app.
Malaysia’s DNS censorship policy is a global threat to Internet freedom
The Malaysian government’s attempt to de-facto ban alternative DNS providers like Cloudflare and Google has faced a massive pushback. But the reversal may be short-lived.
Protect all your devices from ads
Makes you anonymous and your traffic inconspicuous
Helps control web traffic on all your devices
Your feedback helps us improve AdGuard products. To leave a review on the AdGuard website, press the button below.
Got questions about AdGuard Ad Blocker? Contact our support team <mailto:support@adguard.com> .

column1: How easy is it to censor the Web? One word — DNS

Malaysia's recent order for ISPs to redirect DNS queries to government-approved servers may have flown largely under the radar, but it raises serious red flags. Ostensibly, the move is aimed at protecting Malaysians from harmful content like gambling and porn. And while we don't think it's up to any government to teach adults morals, it's even more alarming that this kind of censorship is happening in a relatively democratic country.

At the heart of this issue lies DNS, the system that translates user-friendly web addresses into numerical IP addresses computers use. Traditionally handled by ISPs or third-party services, DNS queries are crucial for seamless web browsing. With this order, the government has given ISPs the power to monitor user activity and decide for users what content they will consume. While encrypted DNS protocols like DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) can offer some protection from this, even their users are not out of the woods.

The enforcement of the policy was put on hold after severe backlash and some technical hiccups. Legitimate websites were inadvertently blocked, and users reported troubles with accessing the Internet. All in all, this turn of events shows the need for a delicate balance between content regulation and user autonomy and also how easy it is to censor the Web. Read the article to find out how to circumvent DNS censorship and what such precedents spell for global Internet freedom.
Brazil bans X and targets VPN users: Are you at risk?

Brazil's recent ban on X has been intensified by a new crackdown on VPN users, who now face steep fines for accessing the platform through such services. While the move aims to enforce the ban, the challenge of monitoring VPN usage raises questions about its effectiveness.
Users migrate to more secure DNS protocols

The shift towards encrypted DNS protocols like DNS-over-TLS is gaining momentum, with secure DNS usage growing substantially. This change helps shield users' browsing activities from eavesdropping by third parties.
Court orders Cloudflare to block sites: a dangerous precedent

Italy attempted to strong-arm Cloudflare into blocking pirate sites, sparking major concerns for the global DNS scene. Such rulings could force DNS providers to enforce regional bans worldwide, which could set a risky precedent for how DNS services are policed globally.
EU launches DNS4EU: Is it good for users?

The EU's DNS4EU is a new public DNS service designed to boost online security with features like malware protection and content filtering. While it aims to enhance user privacy and digital sovereignty, similar benefits are already available through existing services like AdGuard DNS.

column1: Telegram CEO detained, but it’s your privacy that might be on trial

Pavel Durov, CEO of Telegram, has recently been detained in France and is facing an array of preliminary charges. The core allegation is that Durov refused to share data with the French government upon request. While the probe is still unfolding, Durov's arrest has already sparked significant controversy, reigniting the debate over digital privacy and the role of messaging services in protecting user data.

With increasing expectations from users for privacy-focused services — like Telegram — to act as guardians of their data, Durov’s detention has deepened existing concerns about governmental overreach and erosion of trust in governmental institutions not to pry into citizens’ private lives.

The European Union, known for its robust data protection regulations like GDPR, is seen by many as a gold standard for privacy. Any deviation from this ideal, as seen in Durov’s case, undermines confidence in the EU’s commitment to personal data protection. This incident underscores a critical challenge for privacy-centric services: to maintain user trust, they may need to rework their data handling practices. This could mean reducing data storage and ensuring end-to-end encryption for all chats — click below for AdGuard co-founder’s full take on the Telegram situation.
Mozilla dumps ad-tracking code amid growing privacy concerns

Mozilla has removed an ad-tracking code from the latest versions of its mobile browsers: Firefox and Firefox Focus. While Mozilla has historically defended its use, this move comes amid growing scrutiny over its data practices and the introduction of a new ad measurement feature. Does the non-profit want to have its foot in both camps? It increasingly seems so.
How big app stores hurt developers and users

Apple and Google’s dominance over their app stores continues to stifle developers — Telegram’s clash with Apple’s 30% cut demands is just one example. But their restrictive policies impact not just devs, but also users, inflating the costs for them and limiting choice.
No more selling of sensitive location data

In a historic move, the FTC has banned a prominent data broker from selling sensitive location data without user consent. This never-seen-before enforcement of such kind highlights the ongoing effort to curb intrusive data practices and protect user privacy.
Messaging apps up in arms over ‘anti-encryption’ law

Signal, WhatsApp, and other encrypted messaging giants are rallying against the UK’s Online Safety Bill, which they argue threatens the very essence of end-to-end encryption by mandating scans of private messages. This, some believe, could turn secure communications into open books, jeopardizing user privacy.

column1: Taego'da türlü gizemlerle dolu yeni bir yer keşfedildi 👀,"Yenilenmiş Taego dünyası ve Antrenman Modu düzenlemeleri seni bekliyor!
Taego'nun sırlarını merak ediyor musun soulflmS? Hemen 31.2 Güncellemesi'ne dal, tüm sırları gün yüzüne çıkar ve daha fazlası için bizi takip etmeye devam et!
Taego'da tuhaf hadiselerin yaşandığına dair söylentiler dolanıyor. Terk edilmiş bir hastanenin sırlarını açığa çıkaran birbirinden çarpıcı iki video yayınlandı...
Videolara hemen göz atarak Taego'da gerçekte neler olup bittiğini öğren ve gelecek bölümde esrar perdesinin tamamen ortadan kalkmasına hazır ol!

Taego'da yüreğini ağzına getirecek çatışmalara dal! Hospital🏥 gibi yeni mekânlar ve stratejini konuşturabileceğin arazi iyileştirmeleri seni bekliyor! Yenilenen Antrenman Modu'nda sınırsız cephaneyle pratik yap ve Özel Drop'lardan kapabileceğin iki günlük ödülü sakın kaçırma! 😉
Ayrıntılar için hemen aşağıdan güncelleme notlarına göz at!
Uzay temalı yeni Survivor Pass: Zero Gravity'yle yer çekimine meydan oku ve MP5K'nın geliştirilebilir silah kozmetiğiyle teçhizatına sınıf atlat. Üstelik yepyeni Enerji İçeceği kozmetiği de cabası!
Daha fazla ayrıntı eylül ayının Mağaza güncellemesinde!

column1: Chrome makes a U-turn on its course to fade out third-party cookies

Third-party cookies are small pieces of data stored in your browser that track information about you across different websites. Most web browsers have already eliminated them or are on track to do so. Even Google Chrome, one of the last staunch defenders of cookies, had previously agreed to eventually replace them with the Privacy Sandbox API — Google’s allegedly more privacy-friendly solution for targeted advertising.

However, in a recent blog post, Google’s VP Anthony Chavez announced that while the company remains committed to implementing the Privacy Sandbox API, Chrome will not abandon tracking cookies. This is a significant blow to user privacy, as Chrome holds a dominant 65% share of the global browser market.

Admittedly, Google claims it will offer “a new experience” in Chrome that will allow users to “make an informed choice” about allowing or disallowing third-party cookies. While this sounds promising on paper, Google has a long history of implementing dark patterns that subtly influence user choices in ways that benefit the company. We are yet to see what form this “informed choice” will take, but our expectations remain cautious.
Apple accused of “stealing from street musicians”

Apple has reminded the world of the tight grip it holds on the iOS app market by imposing a 30% cut on in-app donations through Patreon, an app that allows creators to support their work without relying on ad revenue. The decision has already sparked a storm of criticism, but will it be enough to prompt any real change?
Privacy Sandbox API isn’t without its flaws

While third-party cookies are undeniably bad for privacy, so is Google’s proposed substitute for them. Privacy Sandbox API effectively turns your browser into an ad auction tool, and privacy experts unanimously agree that it’s a bad alternative.
The time when Google paid $400 million for misleading its users

On the topic of dark patterns, Google holds the dubious distinction of paying the largest fine of its kind for misleading users into believing they had disabled geo-tracking. In reality, the company continued to collect location data to target users with highly personalized ads.
Google’s history of privacy failures revealed

In a somewhat ironic turn of events, it took a data leak for the world to learn about dozens of privacy-related incidents linked to either Google itself or its third-party vendors, and they range from pretty mild to rather troubling.

column1: Kullanım koşullarımıza yönelik güncelleştirmeler,"Merhaba, Bu e-postayı, kullanmakta olduğunuz bir veya daha çok Microsoft ürünü ya da hizmeti için geçerli olan Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi'ni güncelleştirdiğimiz için aldınız. Bu güncelleştirmeleri, koşullarımızı açıklamak, koşulların sizin için şeffaf kalmasını sağlamak ve yeni Microsoft ürün, hizmet ve özelliklerini sözleşme kapsamına eklemek için yapıyoruz.
Hizmet Sözleşmeniz daha anlaşılır hale getirildi

Bu e-postayı, kullanmakta olduğunuz bir veya daha çok Microsoft ürünü ya da hizmeti için geçerli olan Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi'ni güncelleştirdiğimiz için aldınız. Bu güncelleştirmeleri, koşullarımızı açıklamak, koşulların sizin için şeffaf kalmasını sağlamak ve yeni Microsoft ürün, hizmet ve özelliklerini sözleşme kapsamına eklemek için yapıyoruz.
Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi, sizinle Microsoft arasında olan ve Microsoft'un çevrimiçi tüketici ürün ve hizmetlerinin kullanımının tabi olduğu sözleşmedir.

Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi'nin tamamını buradan <https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2091994&clcid=0x41f>  okuyabilirsiniz. Ayrıca, buradan <https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2092201&clcid=0x41f>  SSS sayfamıza giderek en kayda değer değişikliklerin bir özeti de dahil olmak üzere söz konusu güncelleştirmeler hakkında daha fazla bilgi edinebilirsiniz. Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi'nde yapılan güncelleştirmeler 30 Eylül 2024 tarihinden itibaren geçerli olacaktır. 30 Eylül 2024 tarihinde veya sonrasında ürün ve hizmetlerimizi kullanmaya devam ettiğiniz takdirde, güncelleştirilmiş Microsoft Hizmet Sözleşmesi'ni kabul etmiş olursunuz.

Kabul etmiyorsanız bu koşullar geçerlilik kazanmadan önce ürün ve hizmetlerimizi kullanmayı bırakabilir ve Microsoft hesabınızı kapatabilirsiniz. Ebeveyn veya yasal vasiyseniz, satın alma işlemleri de dahil olmak üzere çocuğunuzun kullandığı Microsoft ürün ve hizmetleri de sizin sorumluluğunuzdadır.
Microsoft ürünlerini ve hizmetlerini kullandığınız için teşekkür ederiz.

column1: Chrome warns: Some extensions may stop working soon — don’t panic

Google Chrome has started displaying a rather ominous warning that some extensions, including ad blockers, may soon no longer be supported. If you've seen this message, don't worry too much — it's all part of Google's plan to update its browser for better security and performance.

The update, called Manifest V3, will change how extensions work. The warning might sound alarming because it claims that extensions based on the old platform — Manifest V2, like AdGuard AdBlocker — don't follow ""best practices."" But that doesn’t mean your extension is unsafe. It simply reflects Chrome's move to a newer framework. AdGuard is ahead of the curve, with a new version of our ad blocker that meets the new standards already available in the Chrome Web Store, currently in beta.

The transition to Manifest V3 may bring some changes in how extensions work, but most users won’t notice any big differences in the efficiency of ad-blocking. We’re committed to giving you the reliable features you love.
Ad-Filtering Dev Summit 2024: Insights from AdGuard's CTO

In an interview, AdGuard CTO Andrey Meshkov highlights the importance of the Ad-Filtering Dev Summit in building community and driving innovation. This year's topics include AI and chatbots, the transition to Manifest V3, and new tools for filter list development. You still have time to apply.
Why users are choosing AdGuard VPN?

Curious why some users are switching to AdGuard VPN? We conducted a survey to find out, and the results are in! Discover what users love about our service and the exciting improvements we're planning, including making our protocol open-source.
How ad blocking works: The might behind the magic

Ad blockers might seem like magic, but they actually rely on a sophisticated system of filters — carefully crafted rules maintained by a community of developers — to identify and block ads. Yet, with browsers setting new limits and ad companies constantly evolving their tactics, what's the secret to keeping these blockers effective?
Chrome extensions putting millions at risk

A study reveals that Google's Chrome Web Store is failing to effectively vet extensions, exposing millions of users to security risks. Despite Google's claims of rigorous checks, over 280 million users were found to have installed malware-laden extensions, some of which have lingered in the store for years.
What it took to publish 1st MV3-based ad blocker

With Google Chrome deprecating the old platform for building extensions, Manifest V2, we had to transition to a new one, Manifest V3, or MV3 for short. The journey was not all sunshine and roses, but made it in the end. Learn how.

column1: In this month’s digest, we focus on how Google deals with malicious Chrome extensions and highlight the importance of privacy protection through ad blockers, explore YouTube’s new ad strategy, and discuss Firefox’s controversial tracking feature. Plus, we introduce the beta version of AdGuard Ad Blocker on MV3, cover the latest updates for AdGuard across major platforms and the new features in AdGuard DNS.
Google’s Chrome Web Store infested with dangerous extensions
New research sheds light on the state of extensions in Google’s Chrome Web Store, revealing that the company is doing an exceptionally poor job in purging the bad apples.
Why do people use ad blockers? The reasons are not so obvious, survey shows
The purpose of an ad blocker is obvious from its name. However, ad blocking is far from the only use for them. Our survey results show other reasons, and privacy protection ranks high.
AdGuard Ad Blocker on Manifest V3 enters beta phase
The first ad blocker compatible with Chrome’s Manifest V3 API is now in beta! It has changed a lot since we started developing it. Read on to learn more about this version and the upcoming release.
Server-side ad insertion: YouTube’s new ad strategy challenges ad blockers

YouTube has found a new way to bypass ad blockers by integrating ads directly into video content via “server-side ad insertion,” complicating the detection and blocking of ads. How will ad blockers respond?
Ad-Filtering Dev Summit 2024: Co-hosted by AdGuard

AFDS returns, and we’re co-hosting! Expect two days of tech talks, panels, and networking. And if you’d like to give a presentation, there’s still time to submit your topic. Check out our blog post to find out how.
Firefox enables advertisers to track ad performance by default
Firefox has introduced a feature that helps advertisers track ad performance. Is Mozilla no longer a bastion of privacy?
This month we’ve updated versions of AdGuard Ad Blocker for the four major platforms — Windows, macOS, iOS, and Android. Check out the latest features and improvements in the products you use.
AdGuard DNS v2.8: Automatic device connection and other improvements
In the latest update to AdGuard DNS, we’ve introduced automatic device connection and other enhancements to streamline your experience. Learn more about what’s new in version 2.8.
Protect all your devices from ads
Makes you anonymous and your traffic inconspicuous
Helps control web traffic on all your devices

column1: YouTube plays a trump card against ad blockers

YouTube has unveiled a new tactic to combat ad blockers: ""server-side ad insertion,"" which embeds ads directly into video content. This approach makes it much harder for ad blockers to distinguish ads from the actual video, as both are delivered as a single stream. While ad blockers are currently hamstrung by this method, it is not an obstacle that is completely unsurmoutable.

The new ad delivery method should be seen as part of a bigger picture. Over the past year, YouTube has escalated its anti-ad blocker efforts, starting with pop-up messages and a three-strikes policy threatening to halt video playback. Despite YouTube’s attempts to tighten all the loose screws, ad blockers have adapted but YouTube is likely to throw more wrenches into their works.

This new tactic, though more sophisticated, isn’t entirely new for YouTube, which has used similar methods in its mobile apps. The potential implications are nonetheless significant, particularly for ad-blocking extensions, which struggle more against this technique than standalone apps. The ad-blocking community is not sitting idly by though. We’ve already implemented short-term fixes, and are working on robust strategies to combat YouTube's latest onslaught.
Ad-Filtering Dev Summit is back for 2024

Ad-Filtering Dev Summit returns for its seventh year, co-hosted by AdGuard and eyeo on October 24–25 in Berlin. The event will feature tech talks, presentations, and discussion panels on ad-filtering technology and online privacy. Interested speakers can submit topics by August 30, 2024.
Is Mozilla cozying up to advertisers?

Mozilla is facing backlash for enabling a feature in Firefox that helps advertisers track ad performance by default. Called Privacy-Preserving Attribution (PPA), this feature is aimed at providing a non-invasive alternative to cross-site tracking but has raised privacy concerns.
Tracking and privacy: are they incompatible?
Microsoft ditches cookies, but privacy is still not guaranteed

Microsoft Edge is saying goodbye to third-party cookies and bringing in a new API to take their place. Though Microsoft promises better privacy, we're skeptical. To ensure your data stays private, AdGuard is blocking this new API.
Still relying on Incognito mode? We have bad news

Google has tweaked Chrome's Incognito mode disclaimer, admitting it still tracks user data despite claims of private browsing. This change comes after a $5 billion lawsuit revealed Google continued collecting data in Incognito mode without users' explicit consent.
Chrome’s new ad tool: still not cutting it

Google's proposed replacement for third-party cookies essentially turns the browser into an ad auction tool. AdGuard has already blocked this new API to protect user privacy, as it may still allow background tracking and data sharing.

column1: Survey results: Reasons why people use ad blockers

As the relentless onslaught of online ads continues to encroach on our browsing experiences, more users are turning to ad blockers for reasons that extend well beyond a clean page view. A recent survey by AdGuard and SurveyMonkey shows that a whopping 87% of users are worried about how ads track their data, indicating a growing perception of ads as an acute threat to privacy.

In fact, privacy protection is now one of the top reasons as to why people use ad blockers. Of course, such reasons as clearing away annoying ads and speeding up page loading time are important, but a substantial portion of users now say that they employ ad blockers mainly to protect their privacy. Another big emerging reason is security — over 40% of respondents chose it. Ads can sometimes hide malware or trick you into revealing personal information, so blocking them keeps your devices safer.

These findings underscore a fundamental shift: ad blockers are no longer just about blocking ads for convenience. They have become essential tools that people rely on to keep their online experience smooth, safe, and private, especially in an era where ads seem to have a disturbing grip on our digital lives.
Google Chrome under fire for extension safety

Google Chrome's lax vetting of extensions in its Chrome Web Store was exposed by a recent research. It revealed Google’s substantial failures in detecting dangerous extensions despite the company’s claimed screening rigor.
Extensions can steal your data, but do not panic yet

About 12.5% of Chrome extensions can access sensitive info such as plaintext passwords on major sites like Google and Cloudflare, recent findings show. Does it mean that all extensions with broad permissions are bad?
What’s wrong with Apple and Google app stores

Apple and Google App Stores continue to fail in effectively protecting user privacy, despite their stringent guidelines. Selective enforcement of the rules and lack of tools available to developers make them ineffective in safeguarding user data.
Ad blockers are good for your security, FBI says

The FBI has thrown its weight behind using ad blockers to fight off intrusive ads and security threats. In the spotlight are malicious ads, which lure people into downloading malware and browsing phishing sites.

column1: AdGuard v7.18 for Windows: dealing with Start menu ads
Ads in the Start menu? We don’t think so, Microsoft.

Recently, Microsoft started injecting ads in Windows 11 Start menu, in the form of Microsoft store app recommendations. We covered the news in our blog and promised to deal with them shortly. And now, the time has come.

column2: AdGuard now blocks ads in the Windows 11 Start menu (you can turn this feature on in Settings → Ad Blocker → Disable Windows OS ads)
updated CoreLibs enhances ad blocking functionality by providing even more tools to create powerful filtering rules
updated network drivers improve AdGuard’s compatibility with other network-based apps

column1: This month we’ve been busy releasing a new product — AdGuard VPN for Linux — as well as updating existing ones: for example, we launched a new version of AdGuard for Android with an improved YouTube player. And, of course, we have a couple of interesting privacy stories to tell: a new leak reveals another Google privacy blunder, and the FBI advises users not to use free VPNs.
Meet AdGuard VPN for Linux! In this article you will find the setup guide and our plans for the future.
Free VPNs with premium features can steal your data or even make you an unwitting participant in a crime.
Google’s history of privacy failures revealed
More than once or twice, Google has had privacy problems. The latest leak reveals yet another of the company’s privacy lapses.
Now our YouTube player boasts picture-in-picture mode, recommended videos, quality settings, and more.
Use our new tool, AdGuard DNS Client, to set up Private AdGuard DNS on computers that don’t support encrypted DNS. See the article for detailed instructions.
How we created a safe HTML email renderer

AdGuard created a safe and rich HTML email renderer that supports animation, adaptivity, modern image formats, dark themes, and everything else you would expect from a modern email client. How did we do it and why?
Protect all your devices from ads
Makes you anonymous and your traffic inconspicuous
Helps control web traffic on all your devices
Your feedback helps us improve AdGuard products. To leave a review on the AdGuard website, press the button below.
Got questions about AdGuard Ad Blocker? Contact our support team <mailto:support@adguard.com> .

column1: Mozilla buys ad metrics firm: Still privacy pioneer or compromiser?

Mozilla, long lauded for championing user privacy with its Firefox browser, has raised eyebrows with its recent acquisition of Anonym, an ad metrics company. This move, ostensibly aimed at boosting advertising effectiveness while still maintaining privacy, inevitably makes one question the company’s commitment to its core principles.

Mozilla claims that Anonym will operate in a privacy-preserving manner, safeguarding user data through an array of measures like anonymized insights and differential privacy algorithms. These methods supposedly prevent individual user identification, but privacy isn't just about the ability to unmask an individual user; there's more to it than anonymity.

Mozilla's acquisition of Anonym mirrors the initiatives from tech giants like Google and Microsoft aiming to balance targeted advertising with user privacy. Like Anonym, they have thrown around the ""private"" label a lot in relation to advertising. But the industry's track record shows that simply labeling services ""private"" does not always guarantee they indeed are.
Netflix fully embraces ads with potential free tier

Netflix is reportedly exploring the launch of a free, ad-supported tier in Europe and Asia, marking a significant departure from its ad-free legacy. While not entirely out of the blue, this move raises serious concerns for viewers’ privacy.
Did Microsoft solve the ad privacy puzzle?

Microsoft Edge is getting rid of third-party cookies and rolling out the Ad Selection API to supposedly make ad transactions more secure and private. But there are worries that ad tech companies could still have a say in how things operate, making one wonder if this really guarantees privacy.
Configure your browser for maximum protection

While some browsers claim to already prioritize privacy, you can make them even more private by cranking up your setting to the max. Alternatively, you can strike a comfortable balance between usability and safeguarding data. Here’s how you do it.
Google is getting serious about privacy… or is it?

Google Chrome's move to phase out third-party cookies includes introducing the Protected Audience API to help advertisers while still taking care of privacy, or so it says. Yet, doubts persist over whether this solution is truly private, as the API essentially turns the browser into an ad auction platform.

column1: She is valor, wisdom and benevolence. She is also vengeance. As the quick-witted shinobi assassin, use noise, light and shadows to evade your enemies; infiltrate enemy bases with your grappling hook; assassinate your targets with the hidden blade.

column1: The Creed's most iconic weapon just got reforged. The blade doesn't just spring, it rotates at your command.

column1: Intimidating to face, and even more intimidating to wield. But with equal devastation on each side, it can reach multiple enemies at once and perform deadly assassinations from a distance.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: Don't fight, glide over your enemies using the grappling hook.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: Stay invisible anywhere you go, whether it's atop the roofs, through the snow or under the shallow water.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: Japan’s landscapes captivate with their beauty, yet they remain vulnerable to the ravages of fighting.

column2: LEARN MORE <https://click.updates.ubisoft.com/?qs=76ac81a041eba4f908933fb627eed4b9a2048504ddb66a6a7075c9586f8afa185c250081555414f1a3030f26588e266b4d115b0138e59bbd05302056af5a5742>

column1: He's a legendary samurai who strikes fear into his enemies, but also masks his pain with charm, affability, and charisma. Use his shocking power and precision to smash, bludgeon and destroy the will of Japan's oppressors.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: The Kanabo's purpose can be described in three words. Blunt. Force. Trauma. Its destructive power turns defenses into debris and armor into pulp. But it's also slow on attack and on recovery, making it a high-commitment weapon.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: The katana is what transforms a samurai warrior into a nearly unstoppable force. It is also the most versatile weapon in Yasuke's arsenal, excelling in combat situations, executions and dealing vast amounts of damage.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: Master the katana, and with each swift strike, cast a shadow of fear over your enemies.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

column1: Engage with the environment where every move reshapes the landscape, turning obstacles into opportunities.

column2: <https://ubistatic-a.akamaihd.net/0175/CRM/EMAIL/BATCH/RED/2024/WWCRM8041_AC_Follow_Up/Header/Arrow_Right.png>

Step into the shoes of a stealth-focused shinobi or a combat-oriented samurai. Choose wisely and shape your journey in Feudal Japan!
GIVE YOUR VOICE TO AN NPC

Ever dreamed of being part of the Assassin’s Creed universe? Here’s your shot! Join the dubbing challenge on TikTok and dub famous scenes from past Assassin's Creed games for a chance to become the voice of an NPC in Assassin’s Creed Shadows.
Be among the first to forge your path in a war-torn Japan on November 15th.

Enjoy the full game experience anywhere you go with compatible iPhone and iPad devices. Play the beginning of the game now for free and keep your progression once you've purchased the full game.

column1: Crossing the line? Microsoft pushes ads into system interface

In the latest Windows 11 update, Microsoft has subtly integrated ads into the Start menu. Third-party apps featuring the “Promoted” tag now appear alongside other apps in the Recommended section. While some users may not have noticed this change, it has the potential to litter the Start menu with unnecessary and unwelcome distractions, and at some point they may not be limited to only 3d-party apps.

Beyond the Start menu, Microsoft's aggressive advertising tactics have extended to other facets of the Windows 11 experience. The recent introduction of an ad slot on the Settings home page promoting its Game Pass subscription service underscores this trend. This brazen push for ads, even within core system settings, reflects a troubling pattern of Microsoft putting profit ahead of users.

The upcoming update of the AdGuard app for Windows will block these ads within the system interface. We believe that an uncluttered experience should be the norm, not something that can only be achieved through a complicated opt-out process.
TikTok ban in the US: A boost for VPN market?

As the US edges towards banning TikTok, we foresee a surge in VPN demand, mirroring past social media restrictions. While the ban presents challenges, it may also raise awareness of the importance of VPNs for online privacy and security.
Smart TV getting more and more dumb ads

As more people turn to streaming TV, annoying ads keep popping up on smart TVs, now hawking stuff like cars and drinks. These ads, fueled by data collection, show up on home screens and in apps, and where not. But you can fight back.
From hate to love: Unmarked ads flood X
For a CEO who famously claimed to ""hate"" advertising, Elon Musk's recent advertising decisions have raised eyebrows. The introduction of unreportable spammy ads is just one example.

Discord, once a haven from advertising for gamers, has introduced ads, marking a significant departure from its previous stance. While the current ad format seems relatively unobtrusive, this move could pave the way for more intrusive advertising.

column1: This digest covers Discord’s introduction of ads, Microsoft Edge's cookie policy updates, and Reddit's new restrictions for VPN users. We also delve into YouTube’s recent actions against third-party ad blockers, enhancements to AdGuard Temp Mail, potential TikTok restrictions in the US, and Roku’s innovative yet controversial advertising strategy.
Ads in Discord: from ad-free sanctuary for gamers to ad-infested chaos?
Ads are coming to Discord, a messaging platform beloved by gamers. Why? And what will come out of it? And most importantly, how to block them? We explain.
Microsoft Edge is getting rid of third-party cookies. What about their replacement?
Microsoft Edge is getting rid of third-party cookies — the linchpin of cross-site tracking. But their replacement poses privacy risks as well.
Reddit blocks access for VPN users: what is happening and how to get around it
Reddit has been blocking users who are using VPNs from its site unless they log into their Reddit accounts. Why is that? And what to do?
YouTube crackdown on third-party ad-blocking apps: AdGuard not affected
YouTube has begun blocking playback in third-party applications that violate its API terms. AdGuard does not use the YouTube API and is not affected by this.
AdGuard Temp Mail: From beta to better

It started as a simple beta version, but now it has evolved into a full product! Welcome to the enhanced AdGuard Temp Mail. Read on about our journey to email privacy and what future products are in store for you.
Are they banning TikTok in the US? How to get around the restrictions
Are they banning TikTok in the US? The popular video-sharing platform is not yet blocked for US users, but it can be in the near future. Then a VPN can come in handy.
Not watching TV? Does not matter, Roku will still serve you ads

Roku pursues a patent to display ads on external devices via HDMI, using user data and content recognition. This move could interrupt personal media experiences, raising privacy and user experience concerns.

Last month we released new versions of AdGuard for Mac, AdGuard for Windows, and AdGuard for iOS. Check out the full details on how to make the most of the new features and how they can optimize your AdGuard usage.

column1: This smart TV giant plans to flood your screen with ads

Roku, notorious for prioritizing ads over hardware (and user experience), is pursuing a patent to expand its ad reach beyond its own platform. The patent, titled ""HDMI Customized Ad Insertion,"" reveals a disturbing push by one of the biggest names in set-top box hardware to display ads on external devices such as game consoles or DVD players.

The patent outlines a dystopian scenario where interruptions in media playback trigger potentially intrusive ad placements — think of your wedding reception being hijacked by a champagne ad. To do this, Roku plans to leverage rich user data collected from smart TVs, as well as its ability to identify the content being played through Automatic Content Recognition (ACR) technology.

While the patent is not yet implemented and may never be, Roku's vision for the future encroaches on personal space and represents a troubling trend of prioritizing profit over user experience and privacy. Will ad blockers be able to stop the onslaught of these ads?

Need to sign up for a service without revealing your personal email? AdGuard has you covered with our new temporary free email service! Fresh out of beta, this revamped and improved version is primed and ready for you to try.
TikTok's US fate: the ban is imminent?

With the threat of a total ban on TikTok in the US looming, find out what the chances of this actually happening are, and how VPNs can provide a solution so users can continue to enjoy TikTok without any disruptions.
Microsoft Edge’s cookie replacement tastes sour

Microsoft Edge has announced plans to phase out third-party cookies. This may be something to celebrate — after all, third-party cookies are a notorious tracking tool. But its replacement, the Ad Selection API, raises concerns. It may not provide the privacy users are hoping for.
The dark side of smart TVs
Smart TVs: From seamless viewing to ad onslaught

Smart TVs offered a welcome break from scheduled programming, but they have a dark side. Dive into the invasive world of data collection by TV giants like Vizio and Roku, and discover how your viewing habits are being exploited for profit, leaving your privacy at risk.
Smart TVs are getting smarter, but at what cost?

Samsung's TV Block technology claims to enhance security, but sparks concerns about vendor control and user privacy. It's part and parcel of an alarming trend where users are losing control over their devices, as vendors gain more power over their operation.

column1: The latest patch: Past season treasures returned and new giveaway events!,"
Long time no see, hope everything is well with you. Here we have collected some content that you may be interested in.
The past season treasures are returned in this patch! Don't miss out on the chance to get the extreme outfits you've been wanting.

Using gold as his weapon of choice, Lyam Liu deflects, stuns, and even captures his foes with the power of magnetism. The new hero reservation event has started in-game, don't forget to now to receive massive rewards!
Akos Hu's first special accessory [Timeless Crafts·Roaring Rally], which brings a new effect to his abilities, will be available in-store on Apr 24 PT after the patch
The new hero and new season treasure will be officially launched on May 8 PT. There will be more exciting content waiting for you to discover!

column1: YouTube steps up fight against ad blockers, AdGuard in the clear

YouTube has gone after third-party apps that allow users to watch its videos without those pesky ads. The crackdown specifically targets apps that use YouTube’s official API (application programming interface) to block those ad interruptions.

As a result, the users of these ad-blocking apps may see their videos take too long to load or not load at all with an error message proclaiming that the content is unavailable. It’s all part of YouTube's ongoing quest to vanquish ad blockers — a campaign that’s been raging for about a year now.

AdGuard Ad Blocker, including its Android and iOS apps, remains unaffected. Unlike other ad blockers, AdGuard does not rely on the YouTube API to fend off ads. And while you may consider getting yourself a YouTube Premium subscription — if available in your country — to ensure ad-free experience on all the platforms and eschew uncertainty, the AdGuard apps are still in the game, and continue to block ads without any disruption.
Do you use crypto? Help us by taking this poll

Is crypto a part of your daily life, or do you dabble in it once in a while? Are you a Bitcoin evangelist, an Ethereum enthusiast, or perhaps you lean towards Solana? Take part in our crypto survey, and who knows — there might be something exciting in the works for you!
Reddit is banning VPN users from the site. What gives?

When you’re connected to a VPN and try to access Reddit via a web browser without logging in, you might encounter an unwelcome surprise: an error message urging you to either log in or sign up. Why does Reddit give the cold shoulder to unlogged users? We have some ideas.
How to still watch YouTube with an ad blocker

Ad-blocking community is locked in a war with YouTube and has no intention to give up. If you encounter issues with your ad-blocking app on YouTube, here is a step-by-step guide on how to continue watching videos with the AdGuard ad blocker.
How did YouTube crackdown affect ad blockers?

After YouTube intensified its crackdown on ad blockers, users initially lost confidence in them, and de-installations spiked. However, the situation swiftly rebounded. Just take a look at the numbers! 👀📈
News media and ad blockers can be friends

News media and ad blockers may seem like unlikely allies — media accuse ad blockers of depriving them of ad revenue — but there are reasons to drop the hostility. Research shows that ad blocking can actually increase subscriptions. Here's how.
